A R T I C L E I N F O A B S T R A C T

_Keywords:_

Deep reinforcement learning Automated drug control computing Healthcare IT

In this work, we present a deep reinforcement learning-based approach as a baseline system for autonomous propofol infusion control. Specifically, design an environment for simulating the possible conditions of a target patient based on input demographic data and design our reinforcement learning model-based system so that it effectively makes predictions on the proper level of propofol infusion to maintain stable anesthesia even under dynamic conditions that can affect the decision-making process, such as the manual control of remifentanil by anesthesiologists and the varying patient conditions under anesthesia. Through an extensive set of evaluations using patient data from 3000 subjects, we show that the proposed method results in stabilization in the anesthesia state, by managing the bispectral index (BIS) and effect-site concentration for a patient showing varying conditions.

# Introduction

Advances in deep learning systems, along with their capability to understand complex underlying system features, have motivated the application of such systems to address various healthcare-related chal- lenges \[[1](#_bookmark30)\]. Deep neural networks are especially well-suited to tackle complex problems related to dosage and interface control for different clinical practice purposes \[[2](#_bookmark31),[3](#_bookmark32)\]. Receiving noticeable attention, the field of automated propofol control for supporting effective (yet safe) anesthesia, introduces challenges that match the capabilities of deep learning-based prediction models. Specifically, for clinical protocols such as _total intravenous anesthesia (TIVA)_ used for general anesthesia and procedural sedation, where drugs such as propofol and remifen- tanil are commonly applied, controlling the dosage to assure that the subject (or the patient) remains at a _target bispectral index (BIS)_ is important \[[4](#_bookmark33)\].

Generally, specialized physicians, and anesthesiologists, take the role of drug infusion control during general anesthesia to prevent any incidents and to make sure that the subject is in a stable anesthetic state throughout the operation. This is incredibly important given that improper administration of drug dosage can lead to intraoperative

awareness or hemodynamic instability during operations \[[5](#_bookmark34)\]. Anesthe- siologists take into account many different factors from the patient, including lean body mass, central blood volume, and demographic data when computing the proper dose of drugs for a target patient. However, while is a routine process for skilled anesthesiologists, there is no golden rule on how different factors should be amalgamated to offer an ideal case for patients with different needs. Furthermore, the fact that drugs used for anesthesia have a rapid elimination property and a narrow safety margin, makes decisions even more challenging.

To address such issues, a number of previous works have put effort into designing approaches for propofol dosage suggestions. Specifically, _target controlled infusion (TCI)_ is a commonly used drug infusion control algorithm targeting to suggest specific dosages on a per-subject-basis using a _pharmacokinetic (PK)_ or _pharmacodynamic (PD)_ model \[[6](#_bookmark35),[7](#_bookmark36)\]. With larger datasets, Lee et al. proposed a machine learning model for predicting the impact of drug dosage \[[8](#_bookmark37)\] and Moore et al. ex- ploited a reinforcement learning model for drug infusion control \[[9](#_bookmark38)\]. Unfortunately, the practical applicability of these approaches is still limited given that they do not consider the full diversity of population characteristics (due to limited subject size) or lack the consideration

To cope with these issues, in the early days of the deep learning era, deep reinforcement learning (DRL) and imitation learning have made successful control in dose control \[[10](#_bookmark39),[11](#_bookmark40)\]. Humbert et al. presented a decision support policy that assists the anesthesiologists' infusion of drugs to maintain the optimal hypnotic depth, using only observable information (e.g., heart rate, blood pressure, respiratory rate) \[[10](#_bookmark39)\]. However, a simplified discrete action (e.g., reduce, stay, or increase drug dose) is applied without actual drug dosage prediction. In addi- tion, such DRL or imitation learning-based solution does not consider the demonstration for anesthesiologists. As the explainability and these issues are important in the dose control \[[12](#_bookmark41)\], Schamberg et al. propose continuous control on propofol infusion while using Shapley additive explanations for explainability \[[13](#_bookmark42)\]. Even if it shows improvement, only one type of drug delivery is considered.

Spurred by these trends, this paper presents a novel _deep reinforce- ment learning (DRL)_\-based infusion control system that addresses the limitations of previous work. The main challenge in incorporating and DRL model for drug infusion control is the fact that the states of the model are difficult to properly define given the dynamic nature of the human nerve system. For this, we integrate outputs from the PK/PD model, the _de facto_ model used for understanding the drug-human interactions, to the DRL model. As a result, our proposed system takes into consideration the synergistic effect of anesthetic and analgesic drugs and is designed to handle intra- and inter-subject variations in the propofol effect. Furthermore, given that remifentanil infusion is done manually by anesthesiologists, our system is designed to interact and adapt to such unknown (or difficult-to-predict) external behavior. Note that such anesthesiologists-machine interactions are essential, but are something that has not been deeply considered in previous literature. For this, we formulate and present a patient dynamics model for propofol and remifentanil infusion, which is the basis of a system design for accurate predictions of per-subject effects in anesthesia. Using large- scale clinical open-source data collected from 3000 surgical patients who underwent general surgery between June 2016 and September 2016 at the Seoul National University Hospital, Korea, we showcase the effectiveness of our approach in stabilizing the BIS level of a patient and drug concentration under various realistic scenarios \[[14](#_bookmark43)\]. These findings lead to the design of an explainable agent to assist anes- thesiologists in understanding and effectively reacting to emergency situations, without compromising the high stabilization performance. # Related work

- 1. _Measure of hypnosis_

To measure the brain activity and the desired depth of hypnosis, the BIS is often employed as shown in [Fig.](#_bookmark7) [1](#_bookmark7). A value of 100-90 corresponds to a fully awake state. The level of 90-60 and 60-40 indicate light and moderate hypnosis levels, respectively. The level of deep hypnotic state (40-20) and increasing burst suppression (20- 0) is significantly dangerous. In the standard sedation practice, the anesthesiologist manually adjusts the propofol and remifentanil infu- sion based on the BIS. Prior work showed that BIS not only controls the depth of sedation but also reduces the adverse events associated with sedatives, particularly hypotension, desaturation, and bradypnea, by making it possible to reduce the dose of these drugs \[[15](#_bookmark44),[16](#_bookmark45)\]. TCI using a computer-assisted infusion pump is introduced to calculate the appropriate drug administration based on the BIS level \[[17](#_bookmark46)\]. TIVA using TCI of propofol is widely used for anesthesia and sedation. To improve the efficacy of the treatment and the safety of the patient, research on the discrepancy between predicted BIS and measured BIS during TIVA has increasing attention \[[8](#_bookmark37),[18](#_bookmark47)\].

- 1. _Closed-loop control of hypnosis_

In particular, DRL has recently made exciting progress and has demonstrated remarkable performance in control tasks. Previous re- search has shown the possibility of reinforcement learning (RL) algo- rithms for drug infusion control \[[9](#_bookmark38)\]. However, their RL method ignores the synergism of anesthetic and analgesic drugs, limiting its practical applicability in the real world.

There has been a number of previous efforts related to machine learning targeting clinical applications, including medical concept learning \[[19](#_bookmark28),[20](#_bookmark29)\], pattern classification \[[21](#_bookmark48)\], and predictive health- care \[[22](#_bookmark49)\]. Especially, in specific domains of anesthesia, automated

- **Action Definition:** For defining actions, the agent decides on a

The results in [Table](#_bookmark18) [2](#_bookmark18) show that even an experienced anesthesiologist with more than 10 years of experience showed very high errors in predicting the BIS level with drug injection. Unfortunately, this is also evidence that some form of propofol and remifentanil infusion control is needed to improve anesthesia quality in operation rooms today. Performance from a textbook state-of-the-art approach by Schnider et al. \[[27](#_bookmark54)\] is also disappointing, given the high errors that exceed the tolerable stability bounds.

Fortunately, the results from our proposed deep reinforcement learning model shed light on such current-day limitations. As the results for our three proposed models in [Table](#_bookmark18) [2](#_bookmark18) show, the average cases for the DNNand LSTM+Pred cases fall within the target error bounds. For LSTM, the MDAPE is less than 7.5, but the MDPE slightly exceeds the target stability level. Nevertheless, our prediction-based BIS results show superior performance over manual and traditional BIS estimation methods. We emphasize that the data from the same set of patients are used in the evaluation process. A surprising observation to make from the data is the improvement in performance for the LSTM+Pred model. Compared to LSTMand DNN, we see a dramatic improvement. As briefly mentioned earlier, we conjecture this to be an effect of integrating the future BIS prediction into the reinforcement learning process for propofol infusion control. Since the loss function can utilize the input from the additional DNN, more accurate estimations on propofol infusion can be effectively made.

- 1. _Safety of infusion control_

To prevent patients from waking from anesthetic states, the effect- site concentration (__) and plasma concentration (__) should maintain a certain level throughout a target duration. As discussed earlier, the infusion of propofol and remifentanil causes changes to __ (at heart), which leads to delayed changes in __ (measured at the brain), and this is what initiates diversions in the BIS values. Naturally, the decay in

__ indicates that the patient is waking from anesthesia. Thus, as it is important to reach the target BIS level, it is equally important to consider and maintain the changes in concentrations closely. Specif- ically, clinical literature suggests that an effect-site concentration of less than 2_._0  0_._9 can cause a patient to wake from anesthesia \[[38](#_bookmark65)\]. [Fig.](#_bookmark20) [7](#_bookmark20)(a) presents the remifentanil infusion patterns (RFTN plots) and the resulting __ and __ measurements (RFTN __ and RFTN __ plots) for remifentanil performed by an anesthesiologist during a 10,000- second time frame. Notice that the anesthesiologist injects remifentanil as the concentration diverges far from 2.0. In [Figs.](#_bookmark20) [7](#_bookmark20) (c), (d), and (e) we present the propofol injection patterns (top; PPF plots) and the corresponding __ and __ measurements for propofol (bottom). The results suggest that all three models we test successfully maintain a 2.0- level and systematically inject additional doses when the concentration shows a drop. These results together suggest that our proposed deep reinforcement learning-based approach for propofol infusion control can effectively maintain the anesthesia state of patients.

- 1. _Explainability_

[Fig.](#_bookmark20) [7](#_bookmark20)(b) presents a timeline comparison for the resulting BIS from LSTM+Predwith the actual observed BIS. As mentioned, the LSTM+Pred model adds a special DNN to present explainable evidence on why a target propofol dose is selected from the agent. Specifically, it outputs the expected BIS level of the patient once the suggested propofol dose is injected. While our model shows higher fluctuation levels, compared to the ground truth, we can see from [Fig.](#_bookmark20) [7](#_bookmark20)(b) that the BIS predictions are highly accurate (the largest difference observed is 3 BIS units, which is marginal). Thus, this suggests that our model is capable of offering some level of explainability on its propofol infusion control decisions to anesthesiologists.

- 1. _Target change infusion control_

Experiments until now are performed under the assumption that the system should configure a target BIS of 50. However, we now examine the flexibility of the proposed propofol infusion control system towards different (and changing) BIS levels. [Fig.](#_bookmark19) [6](#_bookmark19) presents experimental results for such a test case, where we dynamically change the target BIS from 50 to 30 and then to 60, 30, 40, and 30. This change request takes place during a 10,000-sec time frame. The pink ''Target'' plots on the topmost figures of the three model cases show this dynamic target BIS change. In the figure, the topmost plot also presents the resulting BIS from our three models. Note that the data from the first 150 s are needed as input of the model; thus, accurate BIS tracking is not made in this timeframe. Nevertheless, once given the inputs, we can see the BIS accurately tracking the target levels (with a short delay). We further analyze this short delay using the figures in the middle, where we show how the models converge to a target BIS. As the three middle plots of [Fig.](#_bookmark19) [6](#_bookmark19) show, all three models successfully track the target within a short period of time. Given that a typical surgery takes up to multiple hours, this small delay is negligible in most cases. Among the three, LSTM+Predshows the fastest convergence to the target BIS. Finally, the bottom-most plots in [Fig.](#_bookmark19) [6](#_bookmark19) present the actual propofol infusion

decisions made by the three models for the convergence experiment. We can see delayed correlations in which when more propofol is injected, we see a drop in BIS (deeper hypnotic state), and suppressing propofol increases the BIS.

- 1. _Optimally control_

We examine how the accuracy metrics, MDPE and MDAPE change with respect to different update intervals. Experiments until now used an update interval of 10 s as recommended by anesthesiologists, but this is actually a human-centered limitation given that it is not prac- tical for anesthesiologists to make decisions faster than this interval. However, with automated systems as proposed in this work, there are chances to control the propofol infusion at a more fine-grain time scale. Thus, we test for shorter update intervals (i.e., 1 and 5 s) and observe the average MDPE and MDAPE for these cases. The results presented in [Table](#_bookmark21) [3](#_bookmark21) indicate that a shorter interval allows for more sensitive control over propofol infusion, which leads to higher accuracy in meeting the target BIS level. This is a very promising result that with the clinical adoption of automated systems for propofol infusion control, more safe and stable anesthesia can be conducted during surgical operations.

- 1. _Achievement in long-horizon_

It is known that RL-based control suffers from a long horizon due to a lack of exploration. To verify whether the proposed control method successfully works or not, we conduct experiments in 2  104 second in- fusion control without additional model training. [Fig.](#_bookmark22) [8](#_bookmark22) shows infusion control by our LSTM+Pred. Even if the target BIS value changes and the control time is relatively long, the BIS level follows the target BIS value. In addition, the ability for the next-time slot of BIS prediction does not diverge as shown in [Fig.](#_bookmark22) [8](#_bookmark22)(a). In the propofol infusion aspect, the amount of propofol dosage shows adaptive change corresponding to the target BIS level updates. That is our LSTM+Predpresents not only BIS stabilization in the long horizon but also provides a reasonable explanation for its control.

# Concluding remarks

While maintaining a stable anesthetic state is important in pre- serving the safety of patients under surgical operations, even for the experienced anesthesiologist, this is a challenging task given the dy- namics of various patient- and situation-related factors. This work presents a deep reinforcement learning-based approach for assisting propofol and remifentanil infusion control for stable anesthesia. For this, we design a PK/PD-based dynamic patient simulator to train the agent with per-patient factors effectively and propose a deep reinforce- ment learning agent for proper propofol infusion control under the in-operation dynamics. Extensive evaluations using real-patient data collected from 3000 patients suggest that the proposed deep reinforce- ment learning-based approach with different baseline deep learning models can effectively make dynamic suggestions on the propofol infusion rate to maintain a stable BIS level and drug concentration. Although our results and system design experiences shared in this work comprehensively suggest that DRL-based infusion control can contribute towards safer anesthesia control-related clinical practices of today, we have not conducted DRL-based infusion control in a real patient, which is our future research direction.
